  digestive: {
    id:'digestive', title:'Digestive Health', icon:'🥦', mode:'health',
    subtitle:'A full-day schedule to optimize your gut microbiome, digestion, and nutrient absorption',
    tasks:[
      {time:'6:00 AM',text:'Wake up and drink 16–20 oz of warm water. Warm water stimulates the gastrocolic reflex — the signal from your stomach to your colon that initiates bowel movement and sets a healthy digestive rhythm.'},
      {time:'6:30 AM',text:'Optional: add lemon juice to your water. Lemon stimulates bile production in the liver, which is essential for fat digestion and helps flush stagnant digestive juices from overnight.'},
      {time:'7:00 AM',text:'Morning movement — a brisk 15–20 minute walk. Physical movement directly stimulates peristalsis (the wave-like contractions that move food through the digestive tract).'},
      {time:'7:30 AM',text:'Breakfast — only if hungry. Do not force an early meal. Eating before you are hungry disrupts the Migrating Motor Complex (MMC), the gut\'s self-cleaning cycle that runs between meals.'},
      {time:'8:00 AM',text:'Probiotic supplement or fermented food — yogurt with live cultures, kefir, kimchi, sauerkraut, or miso. Probiotics replenish beneficial gut bacteria that regulate digestion, immunity, and mood.'},
      {time:'8:30 AM',text:'Eat slowly and chew thoroughly — aim for 20–30 chews per bite. Digestion begins in the mouth. Amylase in saliva starts breaking down carbohydrates, reducing the burden on the stomach.'},
      {time:'9:00 AM',text:'Post-breakfast walk (10–15 min). Walking after meals is one of the most consistently effective habits for reducing bloating and improving gastric emptying.'},
      {time:'10:00 AM',text:'Hydrate — sip water consistently between meals. Staying hydrated keeps the mucosal lining of the gut intact and softens stool for easier transit. Avoid large amounts during meals.'},
      {time:'10:30 AM',text:'Prebiotic snack — a green banana, chicory root, garlic, onion, or oats. Prebiotics are the fiber that feeds your beneficial gut bacteria. Without prebiotics, probiotics cannot thrive.'},
      {time:'11:00 AM',text:'Stress check — take 5 slow deep breaths. The vagus nerve connects the brain directly to the gut. Activating it through deep breathing switches the body into rest-and-digest mode.'},
      {time:'11:30 AM',text:'Movement break — walk or light stretching. The MMC (gut\'s cleaning wave) activates during fasted, relaxed states between meals. Movement supports this process.'},
      {time:'12:00 PM',text:'Lunch — the largest meal of the day. Digestive enzyme activity peaks midday. Include diverse plant foods (aim for 30+ different plants per week — the strongest predictor of a healthy microbiome).'},
      {time:'12:30 PM',text:'Post-lunch walk (15 min). Studies show a 15-minute walk after lunch reduces bloating and accelerates gastric emptying more effectively than any supplement.'},
      {time:'1:00 PM',text:'Digestive enzyme support if needed — papaya (papain), pineapple (bromelain), or a digestive enzyme supplement. These help break down proteins, fats, and carbohydrates.'},
      {time:'1:30 PM',text:'Avoid lying down after eating — remain upright for at least 2 hours. Lying down allows stomach acid to reflux and slows gastric emptying significantly.'},
      {time:'2:00 PM',text:'Hydrate. Herbal teas — ginger, peppermint, or fennel — are excellent between-meal drinks that reduce bloating, relax intestinal smooth muscle, and support bile flow.'},
      {time:'3:00 PM',text:'Fiber-rich snack — apple with skin, pear, carrots, or hummus with vegetables. Soluble fiber feeds beneficial bacteria; insoluble fiber adds bulk and speeds transit time.'},
      {time:'3:30 PM',text:'Light exercise — walking, yoga, or cycling. Regular aerobic exercise increases microbial diversity in the gut, one of the strongest markers of overall digestive and immune health.'},
      {time:'4:30 PM',text:'Abdominal self-massage — 5 minutes of gentle clockwise circular massage. This follows the path of the large intestine and stimulates peristalsis, reducing constipation and gas buildup.'},
      {time:'5:00 PM',text:'Early dinner — aim to finish eating by 7 PM. The gut\'s digestive efficiency drops significantly in the evening. Late eating is linked to acid reflux, poor sleep, and disrupted gut microbiome rhythm.'},
      {time:'5:30 PM',text:'Post-dinner walk (15–20 min). The most important post-meal walk of the day — evening digestion is slowest, and walking significantly compensates by stimulating gastric motility.'},
      {time:'7:00 PM',text:'Stop eating for the night. A 12–16 hour overnight fast allows the MMC to run its full cleaning cycle through the gut, sweeping undigested material and preventing bacterial overgrowth.'},
      {time:'7:30 PM',text:'Herbal tea — chamomile or ginger. Both reduce intestinal inflammation, calm gut smooth muscle, and support the transition into rest-and-digest mode for overnight repair.'},
      {time:'9:00 PM',text:'Gentle yoga or stretching — poses like child\'s pose, supine twists, and happy baby compress and release the abdominal organs, stimulating digestion and relieving trapped gas.'},
      {time:'10:00 PM',text:'Sleep — 7–9 hours. During sleep the gut lining regenerates, the microbiome rebalances, and the MMC completes its final cleaning sweep. Poor sleep is one of the most damaging things you can do to long-term gut health.'},
    ]
  },
